  "nursesNote": "Opioid withdrawal is very uncomfortable but rarely life-threatening, unlike alcohol withdrawal. Early signs are flu-like (anxiety, yawning, tearing, runny nose), followed by nausea, vomiting, diarrhea, cramps, dilated pupils, sweating, and gooseflesh; the COWS scale rates severity. The nurse uses a calm, nonjudgmental approach, supports comfort and hydration, and gives medication-assisted treatment (methadone or buprenorphine; clonidine for autonomic symptoms). Naloxone reverses an opioid overdose.",
  "providerOrders": [
    "Use a calm, nonjudgmental approach (SUD is a disease)",
    "Rate withdrawal severity (e.g., COWS) on a schedule",
    "Support comfort, hydration, and rest",
    "Give MAT as ordered: methadone, buprenorphine, or clonidine",
    "Keep naloxone available for opioid overdose"
  ],
